> In rehearsal for “J. B.” are (left to right) Steve Brooks
’(1. B.) and two soldiers (Sam Schumnn and Stu During.)
 
for
By Karen robinson
5&3 Feature Editor
Lights click on receiving a stage ready -for
action ,music books. The costumes actors move
and leave their predicted pattern on the stage.
They speak amd reach,
”border,” cuts in a voice from the center
section of seats. “Take it from the top again.”
The Grinnell production oi 1.3. is taking
shape.
Rehearsals have been going on for four weeks
now, the first three having rehearsals tour nights
a week, and this week rehearsals every night.
At the beginning of the rehearsal schedules the
actors appear in school clothes to deliver half
italy their new lines, The blocking or arrange
‘ ment and movement of actor is Worked out under
the supervision of Richard Meyer (drama), and
the development ot charactc nation is begun.
“We discuss the way various scenes should be
played and experiment with many. many approaches. Even now we are still working on the
interpretations at some scenes." commented
Meyer,
"You know there have been two versions of
ll}. presented Yale was the first to (live this
play, its interpretation was that of‘ an excellent
url debate between the devil and God. The sets
were realistic and the devil and God moved
freely about the stage. The Broadway version,
directed by Elia taken, was more emotional in
impact. The Devil and God remained hair statiallaly against a nonreullstic set. Our ve ion
is a compromise between the two, We see it as a
three way struggle between God, japan and LB.
We will not try to approximate reality 7 our set
is concerned with providing interesting shapes
ITIlree-wa y Struggle in .I. B.
Yale-croatia y Compromise
and acting areas as much as with suggesting
place or time."
After it while lighting and sets, costumes and
drops are added. Scenes. then whole acts are
given Without causes for instruction. Notes taken
by Meyer are discussed ill the close of the incl,
and general instructions are delivered. '
“Thinking of What comes next is vital." ad—
minister Meyer after a run-through of the first
act. “Prepare the audience by followed a logical
order, Think, move, then Speak, that's the order
OI acting.”
Technical problems must be worked out our—
ing rehearsals The music, which is a tape of the
music composed (or and used in the Broadway
production, must be fitted in, the volume regu—
later. There are Iltile problems such as h0w_‘m
keep newspapers used in one scene from matching
and there are technical Stumpel‘s Such as how
to give the impression of an A-being explosion.
This latter problem was solved by the use OI
lighting and wind sound effects,
interventions such as the need of the stage in
the early evening by other organizations must be
force. “We have to have the patients ot low."
shipped one cast member as he wanted to go on
again after one such intervention.
But these rehearsals are only a preparation
for the crucial time when the theater is full and
the real performance begins,
Meyer said, “We hope that students will e .
periodic the play itself rather than sitting ea
1y including the themes or their Junior Liberal
Arts Exam. Comedy calls for this type at peter-tn,
ment, but tragedy needs emotional involvement
Students should be caught up in the specially ot
the play and then analyze in retrospect.”
