éridge,
Ed. note; Bill sherman, class oi 1951, is a travel
scholar in china.
Operating under the rule. The best way to
know it is to see it," the male continuing of Gr-initial
in Africa undertake a safari through East africa. This
journey took place during our seven week summer
vacation. The distances being rather great, walking
was out at the question, so we reported to a tourwhccled monster known as the Gray Gern. ln days
man's language this refers to a 1956 Land Rovertruck, a bit the worse for wear when we started and
even more so now. With beds. cooking store, and julie
or equipment we became a sell sufficient unit, a fact
which proved very useful
Malosa school being located in the southern part
or. swaziland, we first had to universe the Gun miles
to the northern tip of the country. Roads were ins
produced here about so years ago but one could hardly
say that an extensive turnpike system had been de—
allowed. Thus .we founded along, at times not being
certain which end was tip, over roads that make the
Lake Acre route seem like a super highway. There
are many times when one might question whether
they are even one lane. However. the country through
int'high we passed is some ot the most beautiful l have
ever seen. but at the same time extremely promotion,
These mountains and gallery are from the southern
end of the Great girl. Valley, a'phenomenon ot na»
sure quite unique in itself.
ALL ALONG THE way one sees the typical tiny
quaint that one otteii for-gets the applying state ot
poverty which they represent, a fact which can not
help but to around the mind oi one coming front
Galbrailh's Attlnent Society The urban centers
through witch fire passes are images ol a tr-ontiertown in the wild west with the row at Asian stores,
police station, and government headquarters or bomb
surrounded by native hits
The people themselves are extremely friendly. al—
tlrouglr a bit she ot strange characters such as both
and german These rural people seem very happy and
concern‘ut, and quite spyware ot the rights ot so-called civilized modern society. There may be much
truth in the old saying, “insurance is bless."
Oh we drive until reaching the customers post,
where after the usual amount of red tape plus coin»
operations over a wrong engine number on the Gray
her-ii, we pass into Tanganyika. From here on we are
aware of a noticeable rinprovemcnt in conditions The
land, although still very maintaining, begins to open
up. with much less brush, larger fields, more specials
hits and better dressed people Here and there we
see final and tea estates with some machinery whlcll
makes an old town boy feel more at home One flat
tire, two electrical tires, one delay due to happens
and two days later, we reach the center of Tanganyika Here the country is much dried, but the liver
stock population is considerable heather, although the
quantity tar outweighs the quality.
From here we push on toward the coast and car-
l track, sherman, Tours East Africa
development with many estates and much better
roads, some even saved. We have now come from
the high cool mountains to the low scacoast where
temperatures, humidity, and rainfall show remarkable
increases.
The city ol car is an interesting mixture of old
and new: of European, Arab and african. Land is
no problem so the city is spread over a wide area
with government buildings and shopping center in the
middle around the harbor. The whole atmosphere is
very metropolitan Having taken advantage of advertisements ot the city, we made corporations for a
visit to the island of Zanzibar, center ot old Arab
slave trade. Zanzibar is located 45 miles from car
and hoping to get the real teen. we chose to go over
by native boat called a show.__
As things turned out we get more of a real feel
than expected. These shows are the present versions
of those used by the Arab readers for many centuries
along the coast. Many still use fails but others like
the one we took have been fitted with engines. They
paul small loads of tonight between the ports along
the coast. The captain and crew were just like out of
a book and of course could speak almost no English
so conversation was limited, We reported at 5 pm,
and arrived in Zanzibar harbor at 1 am. where we
answered for the night. it was a wonderful star-lit
night for sleeping. but trying to back out on files oi
rope, oil drums, packs of grain and fruit made us
aw that this was not the smaller Hilton. Next
mud hits with grass rooms which are the homes of E5 .
the majority of nations. They seem so natural and vanilla.
